import{_ as t,o,c as i,ag as n}from"./chunks/framework.DwYrYzXn.js";const u=JSON.parse('{"title":"","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"plan/license-rollup.md","filePath":"plan/license-rollup.md"}'),l={name:"plan/license-rollup.md"};function a(s,e,r,c,p,d){return o(),i("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[n("<p>The current tempo-registry App (Firestore Hosting, Cloud Functions, etc) allows the User to &#39;upgrade&#39; their current &#39;abc&#39; license to a new &#39;abc&#39; + &#39;xyz&#39; license, by providing the new license key. The process is as follows:</p><ol><li>User goes to the tempo-registry App, and selects the Update License path.</li><li>They click on the scopes they want (we are still working out the online payments, so forget that for now)</li><li>When they click the button, our Cloud Function will create a new JWT that contains a. the new scopes they clicked / paid for b. for any old scopes not covered above, if they are unexpired, we include the latest-expiry version c. all our other standard Tempo JWT properties.</li></ol><p>In this way, if they &#39;forget&#39; to include an existing scope in their new selection, we will auto-include it for them, and they will not lose access to any of their currently entitled functionality.</p><p>Effectively, they will now have an additional License.</p><ul><li>the old license will continue to be valid until it expires</li><li>the new license will be valid until it expires</li><li>And they can use either license key in their Tempo Runtime.</li></ul><p>This raises the question as to how the App should handle a user&#39;s &#39;checkmark&#39; on an already-selected (and unexpired) scope. Option A: do we even allow it, or block already-owned scopes ? The App currently lets them re-select any scope, and extend the expiry-date for that scope (via a dropdown &#39;years&#39; multiplier).</p><p>Option B: do we grey out or otherwise visually distinguish already-owned scopes?</p><p>*~~~~~ At the end of the day, we want a process that is easy to manage and intuitive. We do not want a User to have to come back every time one of the Scopes expires and mint a new License. The introduction of paid-Plugins makes this even more complex... do we let them extend (with payment) a scope that they already own?</p>",8)])])}const y=t(l,[["render",a]]);export{u as __pageData,y as default};
